# TypeScript & React Coding Standards

## TypeScript Configuration

This project uses TypeScript (currently `strict: false` in tsconfig). Prefer explicit types, avoid `any`, and use type guards for `unknown`. Follow these patterns:

### Type Safety

- Prefer `unknown` over `any` for values from external sources; narrow with type guards.
- Avoid `as` casts; use type guards or validation (e.g. Zod) when possible.
- Use explicit return types on exported functions when they clarify the API.

### Type Definitions

```typescript
// ✅ Use explicit interfaces for props
interface ComponentProps {
  title: string;
  isVisible?: boolean;
  onAction: () => void;
}

// ✅ Use type aliases for complex types
type UserProfile = {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  email: string;
};

// ✅ Export types from barrel files
export type { ComponentProps, UserProfile } from "./types";
```

### Path Aliases

- Always use `@/` prefix for internal imports
- Configured in [tsconfig.json](mdc:tsconfig.json): `"@/*": ["./src/*"]`

```typescript
// ✅ Correct path usage
import { Button } from "@/shared/ui";
import { useUserProfile } from "@/entities/user";
import { Login } from "@/features/authenticate-user";

// ❌ Avoid relative imports
import { Button } from "../../../shared/ui/button";
```

## React Patterns

### Component Structure

```typescript
/**
 * Component Description
 *
 * Brief explanation of what this component does
 * and its main responsibilities.
 */

"use client"; // Only for client components

import React from "react";
import { Button } from "@/shared/ui";

interface ComponentProps {
  // Props definition
}

export const Component = ({ prop1, prop2 }: ComponentProps) => {
  // Component logic

  return <div>{/* JSX content */}</div>;
};
```

### Hooks Patterns

```typescript
// ✅ Custom hooks in model/ segment
export const useCustomHook = () => {
  const [state, setState] = useState();

  useEffect(() => {
    // Effect logic
    return () => {
      // Cleanup
    };
  }, []);

  return { state, setState };
};

// ✅ Export hooks from barrel files
export { useCustomHook } from "./model/useCustomHook";
```

## Code Organization

### File Naming

- Components: `PascalCase.tsx` (e.g., `UserProfile.tsx`)
- Hooks: `useCamelCase.ts` (e.g., `useUserProfile.ts`)
- Utilities / API files: `kebab-case.ts` (e.g., `format-date.ts`, `get-script.query.ts`) — see [naming-conventions.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/naming-conventions.mdc)
- Types: `types.ts` or `types/index.ts`

### Export Patterns

```typescript
// ✅ Named exports for components (preferred; FSD uses barrel re-exports)
export const Button = () => {
  /* ... */
};

// ✅ Default export only for Next.js pages (App Router)
export default function Page() {
  /* ... */
}

// ✅ Re-export from barrel files
export { Button } from "./button/button";
export { Input } from "./input/input";
```

## Performance Considerations

### React Optimization

```typescript
// ✅ Use React.memo for expensive components
export const ExpensiveComponent = React.memo(({ data }) => {
  return <div>{/* expensive rendering */}</div>;
});

// ✅ Use useMemo for expensive calculations
const expensiveValue = useMemo(() => {
  return heavyCalculation(data);
}, [data]);

// ✅ Use useCallback for stable function references
const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
  onAction();
}, [onAction]);
```

### Bundle Optimization

- Use dynamic imports for code splitting
- Import only what you need from libraries
- Avoid importing entire libraries when possible
